<p>
  The Brittain line, long associated with military service and steadiness, also continued to
  express those values into the twentieth century. The legacy of duty did not end with earlier
  generations like Burrell Brittain. It echoed forward through later family members whose lives
  were shaped by service, responsibility, and commitment during times of national challenge.
</p>

<p>
  One tangible artifact of that legacy is the draft card of <strong>O. W. Lee Sr.</strong>.
  Documents like this bridge the distance between past and present. They are reminders that
  global events—wars, mobilizations, and moments of uncertainty—were experienced directly by
  members of this family. The draft card represents not only a legal requirement, but a moment
  when history intersected personally with the Lee and Brittain inheritance of service.
</p>

